</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Iodine 125 (<sup>125</sup>I) radioactive seed localization has emerged as a reliable and safe alternative to wire localization for guidance during the surgical resection of nonpalpable breast lesions. The breast imager has a responsibility to be familiar with the general principles of this evolving technique, including its advantages and disadvantages as well as the technical differences involved in placement of seeds versus traditional wire localization. Although placement of <sup>125</sup>I seeds is conceptually similar to wire placement, there are additional technical considerations and safety measures that need to be addressed and implemented when radioactive seeds are used. We draw from our experience with more than 1000 cases of radioactive seed localization since inception of our program in 2009 to provide illustrative examples of not only the proper technique of radioactive seed localization, but also mishaps that may occur during this procedure, along with practical suggestions to prevent these problems. We examine some of the difficulties that we have encountered during radioactive seed localization at our institution, including bone wax mimicking the seed, the inadvertent deployment of seeds, the need for multiple seeds or supplemental wires, problematic seed locations, and difficulty in surgical retrieval of the seed. Recognizing the potential pitfalls of radioactive seed localization and understanding the appropriate guidelines and precautions for the safe, secure handling and placement of radioactive seeds is essential for a successful radioactive seed localization program.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2015</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2015140293">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2015140293">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig1a.jpeg" height="598" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Radioactive seed assemblies. <b>(a)</b> The loose seed tray assembly used for self-loaded needles includes a hemostat for handling the seed, the loose seed within a sterile glass vial (black arrow), a sealed package of bone wax (yellow arrow), and an 18-gauge coaxial spinal needle. <b>(b)</b> The preloaded needle obtained from a manufacturer (IsoAid, Port Richey, Fla) comes presterilized with a stopper (arrow) to help prevent premature deployment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig1b.jpeg" height="429" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Radioactive seed assemblies. <b>(a)</b> The loose seed tray assembly used for self-loaded needles includes a hemostat for handling the seed, the loose seed within a sterile glass vial (black arrow), a sealed package of bone wax (yellow arrow), and an 18-gauge coaxial spinal needle. <b>(b)</b> The preloaded needle obtained from a manufacturer (IsoAid, Port Richey, Fla) comes presterilized with a stopper (arrow) to help prevent premature deployment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig2a.jpeg" height="577" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Proper technique for occluding the needle tip of the loose seed assembly with bone wax. <b>(a)</b> After removing the stylet, gently scrape the needle tip across the surface of the bone wax before placement of the seed within the lumen of the needle. <b>(b)</b> Too little wax (left) can allow premature deployment of the seed. The proper amount of wax (center) completely and cleanly occludes the needle tip orifice. Too much wax (right) may not only lead to difficulty in identifying the seed during US placement, but may also cause adherence of the seed to the needle tip during deployment into the breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig2b.jpeg" height="801" width="849" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Proper technique for occluding the needle tip of the loose seed assembly with bone wax. <b>(a)</b> After removing the stylet, gently scrape the needle tip across the surface of the bone wax before placement of the seed within the lumen of the needle. <b>(b)</b> Too little wax (left) can allow premature deployment of the seed. The proper amount of wax (center) completely and cleanly occludes the needle tip orifice. Too much wax (right) may not only lead to difficulty in identifying the seed during US placement, but may also cause adherence of the seed to the needle tip during deployment into the breast.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig3a.jpeg" height="470" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> US-guided seed localization of a left breast invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Left breast US image clearly demonstrates the seed (arrow) to be located within the targeted breast mass. <b>(b, c)</b> Left craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> and left mediolateral <b>(c)</b> digital mammographic images reconfirm that the seed (arrow) has been accurately deployed within the breast mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig3b.jpeg" height="932" width="796" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> US-guided seed localization of a left breast invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Left breast US image clearly demonstrates the seed (arrow) to be located within the targeted breast mass. <b>(b, c)</b> Left craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> and left mediolateral <b>(c)</b> digital mammographic images reconfirm that the seed (arrow) has been accurately deployed within the breast mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig3c.jpeg" height="932" width="780" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> US-guided seed localization of a left breast invasive ductal carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Left breast US image clearly demonstrates the seed (arrow) to be located within the targeted breast mass. <b>(b, c)</b> Left craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> and left mediolateral <b>(c)</b> digital mammographic images reconfirm that the seed (arrow) has been accurately deployed within the breast mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig4a.jpeg" height="1053" width="765" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Mammographically guided seed localization of a right breast biopsy clip and faint residual microcalcifications representing high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ. <b>(a)</b> A grid system is used for initial placement of the needle containing the seed. In this case, a right lateromedial approach was used. <b>(b, c)</b> Sequential right craniocaudal digital mammographic images show the needle tip at the target <b>(b)</b> and subsequent deployment of the seed (arrow) within the intended location <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Orthogonal digital mammographic image (right lateromedial view) shows accurate deployment of the seed (arrow) within the target.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig4b.jpeg" height="1054" width="809" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Mammographically guided seed localization of a right breast biopsy clip and faint residual microcalcifications representing high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ. <b>(a)</b> A grid system is used for initial placement of the needle containing the seed. In this case, a right lateromedial approach was used. <b>(b, c)</b> Sequential right craniocaudal digital mammographic images show the needle tip at the target <b>(b)</b> and subsequent deployment of the seed (arrow) within the intended location <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Orthogonal digital mammographic image (right lateromedial view) shows accurate deployment of the seed (arrow) within the target.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig4c.jpeg" height="1024" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Mammographically guided seed localization of a right breast biopsy clip and faint residual microcalcifications representing high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ. <b>(a)</b> A grid system is used for initial placement of the needle containing the seed. In this case, a right lateromedial approach was used. <b>(b, c)</b> Sequential right craniocaudal digital mammographic images show the needle tip at the target <b>(b)</b> and subsequent deployment of the seed (arrow) within the intended location <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Orthogonal digital mammographic image (right lateromedial view) shows accurate deployment of the seed (arrow) within the target.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig4d.jpeg" height="1023" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span> Mammographically guided seed localization of a right breast biopsy clip and faint residual microcalcifications representing high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ. <b>(a)</b> A grid system is used for initial placement of the needle containing the seed. In this case, a right lateromedial approach was used. <b>(b, c)</b> Sequential right craniocaudal digital mammographic images show the needle tip at the target <b>(b)</b> and subsequent deployment of the seed (arrow) within the intended location <b>(c)</b>. <b>(d)</b> Orthogonal digital mammographic image (right lateromedial view) shows accurate deployment of the seed (arrow) within the target.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig5a.jpeg" height="491" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Stereotactically guided seed localization of a right breast invasive lobular carcinoma. A prone digital stereotactic table was used (LoRad; Hologic, Danbury, Conn). <b>(a)</b> A stereotactic pair of craniocaudal right breast images demonstrates the seed (arrows) to be deployed into the targeted mass, adjacent to the biopsy clip. <b>(b, c)</b> Postprocedure right craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> and right mediolateral <b>(c)</b> digital mammographic views reconfirm accurate placement of the seed (arrow) into the malignant mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig5b.jpeg" height="918" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Stereotactically guided seed localization of a right breast invasive lobular carcinoma. A prone digital stereotactic table was used (LoRad; Hologic, Danbury, Conn). <b>(a)</b> A stereotactic pair of craniocaudal right breast images demonstrates the seed (arrows) to be deployed into the targeted mass, adjacent to the biopsy clip. <b>(b, c)</b> Postprocedure right craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> and right mediolateral <b>(c)</b> digital mammographic views reconfirm accurate placement of the seed (arrow) into the malignant mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig5c.jpeg" height="919" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Stereotactically guided seed localization of a right breast invasive lobular carcinoma. A prone digital stereotactic table was used (LoRad; Hologic, Danbury, Conn). <b>(a)</b> A stereotactic pair of craniocaudal right breast images demonstrates the seed (arrows) to be deployed into the targeted mass, adjacent to the biopsy clip. <b>(b, c)</b> Postprocedure right craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> and right mediolateral <b>(c)</b> digital mammographic views reconfirm accurate placement of the seed (arrow) into the malignant mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig6.jpeg" height="1133" width="500" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> A specimen sock is placed over the canister intake and will trap a seed that has been inadvertently suctioned from the surgical bed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig7a.jpeg" height="470" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Removal of the seed from the inked surgical specimen. <b>(a)</b> A gloved gamma probe is used to determine the approximate location of the seed before specimen cut-down. <b>(b)</b> Once the seed is located, a hemostat is used to remove it (circle) from the specimen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig7b.jpeg" height="614" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Removal of the seed from the inked surgical specimen. <b>(a)</b> A gloved gamma probe is used to determine the approximate location of the seed before specimen cut-down. <b>(b)</b> Once the seed is located, a hemostat is used to remove it (circle) from the specimen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig8a.jpeg" height="630" width="851" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Bone wax mimics seed during US-guided RSL. <b>(a)</b> An echogenic line (arrow) seen in the target during US, presumably excessive bone wax, was thought to represent an accurately placed seed. <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure digital mammogram does not demonstrate a seed within the breast (only the original biopsy clip is seen). <b>(c)</b> A second seed was subsequently placed at the target (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig8b.jpeg" height="618" width="813" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Bone wax mimics seed during US-guided RSL. <b>(a)</b> An echogenic line (arrow) seen in the target during US, presumably excessive bone wax, was thought to represent an accurately placed seed. <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure digital mammogram does not demonstrate a seed within the breast (only the original biopsy clip is seen). <b>(c)</b> A second seed was subsequently placed at the target (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig8c.jpeg" height="618" width="863" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span> Bone wax mimics seed during US-guided RSL. <b>(a)</b> An echogenic line (arrow) seen in the target during US, presumably excessive bone wax, was thought to represent an accurately placed seed. <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure digital mammogram does not demonstrate a seed within the breast (only the original biopsy clip is seen). <b>(c)</b> A second seed was subsequently placed at the target (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig9a.jpeg" height="940" width="668" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Inadvertent deployment of a self-loaded seed during mammographically guided RSL. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral digital mammogram of the right breast with the localization grid in place shows the self-loaded needle in appropriate position. The breast was released from compression and repositioned for an orthogonal image, at which point the seed was inadvertently deployed into the lateral portion of the breast. A second seed was successfully placed adjacent to the mass in the medial portion of the breast. <b>(b)</b> Subsequently obtained craniocaudal image demonstrates the misplanted seed in the lateral portion of the breast (arrow), whereas the targeted mass, correctly placed seed, and needle tip are in the medial portion (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig9b.jpeg" height="940" width="807" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Inadvertent deployment of a self-loaded seed during mammographically guided RSL. <b>(a)</b> Mediolateral digital mammogram of the right breast with the localization grid in place shows the self-loaded needle in appropriate position. The breast was released from compression and repositioned for an orthogonal image, at which point the seed was inadvertently deployed into the lateral portion of the breast. A second seed was successfully placed adjacent to the mass in the medial portion of the breast. <b>(b)</b> Subsequently obtained craniocaudal image demonstrates the misplanted seed in the lateral portion of the breast (arrow), whereas the targeted mass, correctly placed seed, and needle tip are in the medial portion (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig10a.jpeg" height="1094" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Inadvertent deployment of a self-loaded seed during mammographically guided RSL. <b>(a)</b> Lateromedial digital image of the left breast was taken after the RSL procedure was complicated by a vasovagal reaction experienced by the patient. The needle tip is adjacent to the target with the seed misplanted into the superior part of the breast (arrow). <b>(b)</b> A second seed was placed through the existing needle, and a postprocedure lateromedial digital image shows accurate placement of the second seed at the target (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig10b.jpeg" height="1094" width="776" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Inadvertent deployment of a self-loaded seed during mammographically guided RSL. <b>(a)</b> Lateromedial digital image of the left breast was taken after the RSL procedure was complicated by a vasovagal reaction experienced by the patient. The needle tip is adjacent to the target with the seed misplanted into the superior part of the breast (arrow). <b>(b)</b> A second seed was placed through the existing needle, and a postprocedure lateromedial digital image shows accurate placement of the second seed at the target (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig11a.jpeg" height="1398" width="524" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Misplanted seed during mammographically guided RSL that required placement of supplemental wires. <b>(a)</b> A self-loaded needle is inappropriately advanced into the breast and a seed subsequently deployed, despite the needle length being too short to reach the targeted calcifications (oval). Two supplemental wires were necessary to bracket the target. <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure digital mammogram shows the misplanted seed (arrow) and two wires bracketing the calcifications (oval).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig11b.jpeg" height="774" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Misplanted seed during mammographically guided RSL that required placement of supplemental wires. <b>(a)</b> A self-loaded needle is inappropriately advanced into the breast and a seed subsequently deployed, despite the needle length being too short to reach the targeted calcifications (oval). Two supplemental wires were necessary to bracket the target. <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure digital mammogram shows the misplanted seed (arrow) and two wires bracketing the calcifications (oval).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig12.jpeg" height="982" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Placement of three seeds in one breast required approval from the RSO. A third seed (white arrow) was placed to localize a second malignant mass after one seed (black arrow) was misplanted laterally, and a second seed (arrowhead) had been correctly placed to localize the medial, targeted mass.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig13.jpeg" height="649" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Placement of three seeds in one breast required approval from the RSO. Two seeds (oval) were used to bracket malignant calcifications more anteriorly, and a third seed (arrow) localizes a posterior malignant mass and biopsy clip.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig14a.jpeg" height="555" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Radioactive seed implanted within the hydrogel portion of a biopsy clip. <b>(a)</b> Postprocedure US image shows the echogenic seed within the bioabsorbable polymer of the clip. <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure digital mammogram shows the seed (arrow) to be adjacent to the metallic portion of the clip, likely within the gelatinous substance.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig14b.jpeg" height="724" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Radioactive seed implanted within the hydrogel portion of a biopsy clip. <b>(a)</b> Postprocedure US image shows the echogenic seed within the bioabsorbable polymer of the clip. <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure digital mammogram shows the seed (arrow) to be adjacent to the metallic portion of the clip, likely within the gelatinous substance.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig15.jpeg" height="654" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Digital image of a specimen sock shows a biopsy clip (arrow) within the sock. The image was obtained after the clip was not located on the surgical specimen radiograph and was not found within the surgical bed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig16a.jpeg" height="1065" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Radioactive seed placement confirmed with the aid of a chest radiograph. <b>(a)</b> Initial postprocedure lateromedial digital mammogram does not show the seed because of its far posterior and medial position, showing only the clip (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure chest radiograph shows the seed (arrow), but not the clip. <b>(c)</b> Repeat mammogram demonstrates both the clip (arrow) and the seed (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig16b.jpeg" height="619" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Radioactive seed placement confirmed with the aid of a chest radiograph. <b>(a)</b> Initial postprocedure lateromedial digital mammogram does not show the seed because of its far posterior and medial position, showing only the clip (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure chest radiograph shows the seed (arrow), but not the clip. <b>(c)</b> Repeat mammogram demonstrates both the clip (arrow) and the seed (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig16c.jpeg" height="1011" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Radioactive seed placement confirmed with the aid of a chest radiograph. <b>(a)</b> Initial postprocedure lateromedial digital mammogram does not show the seed because of its far posterior and medial position, showing only the clip (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Postprocedure chest radiograph shows the seed (arrow), but not the clip. <b>(c)</b> Repeat mammogram demonstrates both the clip (arrow) and the seed (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig17.jpeg" height="1050" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Gadolinium-enhanced MR image (not shown) depicted a small amount of suspicious, residual enhancement in this patient with positive margins at lumpectomy. Craniocaudal digital mammogram obtained during RSL shows the medial seed (arrow) located at the posterior margin of the postsurgical fluid collection (arrowheads) in the region of suspicious enhancement. (A second seed visible in this image localizes a biopsy clip at the site of a second lesion.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig18a.jpeg" height="1079" width="576" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> Close proximity of seeds can limit detection of separate radioactive sites. <b>(a)</b> Digital mammogram shows two seeds that were successfully placed approximately 2–3 cm apart along the margins of the targeted calcifications. <b>(b)</b> The surgeon was unable to differentiate the two radioactive seed counts intraoperatively and, therefore, did not recover both seeds in one specimen. Only one seed can be identified in the surgical specimen radiograph.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig18b.jpeg" height="480" width="899" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> Close proximity of seeds can limit detection of separate radioactive sites. <b>(a)</b> Digital mammogram shows two seeds that were successfully placed approximately 2–3 cm apart along the margins of the targeted calcifications. <b>(b)</b> The surgeon was unable to differentiate the two radioactive seed counts intraoperatively and, therefore, did not recover both seeds in one specimen. Only one seed can be identified in the surgical specimen radiograph.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2015140293/asset/images/large/rg.2015140293.fig19.jpeg" height="860" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span> Seed localization of both the primary breast malignancy and a metastatic axillary lymph node was performed. Right mediolateral oblique digital mammogram demonstrates a seed within a biopsy-proven metastatic lymph node.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2015140293&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Gray RJ, Salud C, Nguyen K, et al. Randomized prospective evaluation of a novel technique for biopsy or lumpectomy of nonpalpable breast lesions: radioactive seed versus wire localization. <em>Ann Surg Oncol</em> 2001;8(9):711–715.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/s10434-001-0711-3">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11597011/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Randomized+prospective+evaluation+of+a+novel+technique+for+biopsy+or+lumpectomy+of+nonpalpable+breast+lesions%3A+radioactive+seed+versus+wire+localization&amp;author=RJ+Gray&amp;author=C+Salud&amp;author=K+Nguyen&amp;publication_year=2001&amp;journal=Ann+Surg+Oncol&amp;pages=711-715&amp;doi=10.1007%2Fs10434-001-0711-3&amp;pmid=11597011">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Gray RJ, Pockaj BA, Karstaedt PJ, Roarke MC. Radioactive seed localization of nonpalpable breast lesions is better than wire localization. <em>Am J Surg</em> 2004;188(4):377–380.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.amjsurg.2004.06.023">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15474429/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Radioactive+seed+localization+of+nonpalpable+breast+lesions+is+better+than+wire+localization&amp;author=RJ+Gray&amp;author=BA+Pockaj&amp;author=PJ+Karstaedt&amp;author=MC+Roarke&amp;publication_year=2004&amp;journal=Am+J+Surg&amp;pages=377-380&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.amjsurg.2004.06.023&amp;pmid=15474429">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">McGhan LJ, McKeever SC, Pockaj BA, et al. Radioactive seed localization for nonpalpable breast lesions: review of 1,000 consecutive procedures at a single institution. <em>Ann Surg Oncol</em> 2011;18(11):3096–3101.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1245/s10434-011-1910-1">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21947587/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Radioactive+seed+localization+for+nonpalpable+breast+lesions%3A+review+of+1%2C000+consecutive+procedures+at+a+single+institution&amp;author=LJ+McGhan&amp;author=SC+McKeever&amp;author=BA+Pockaj&amp;publication_year=2011&amp;journal=Ann+Surg+Oncol&amp;pages=3096-3101&amp;doi=10.1245%2Fs10434-011-1910-1&amp;pmid=21947587">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hughes JH, Mason MC, Gray RJ, et al. A multi-site validation trial of radioactive seed localization as an alternative to wire localization. <em>Breast J</em> 2008;14(2):153–157.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1524-4741.2007.00546.x">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18248562/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=A+multi-site+validation+trial+of+radioactive+seed+localization+as+an+alternative+to+wire+localization&amp;author=JH+Hughes&amp;author=MC+Mason&amp;author=RJ+Gray&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=Breast+J&amp;pages=153-157&amp;doi=10.1111%2Fj.1524-4741.2007.00546.x&amp;pmid=18248562">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">5.</div><div id="r5" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Sung JS, King V, Thornton CM, et al. Safety and efficacy of radioactive seed localization with I-125 prior to lumpectomy and/or excisional biopsy. <em>Eur J Radiol</em> 2013;82(9):1453–1457.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ejrad.2013.04.008">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23684386/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Safety+and+efficacy+of+radioactive+seed+localization+with+I-125+prior+to+lumpectomy+and%2For+excisional+biopsy&amp;author=JS+Sung&amp;author=V+King&amp;author=CM+Thornton&amp;publication_year=2013&amp;journal=Eur+J+Radiol&amp;pages=1453-1457&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.ejrad.2013.04.008&amp;pmid=23684386">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">6.</div><div id="r6" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Pavlicek W, Walton HA, Karstaedt PJ, Gray RJ. Radiation safety with use of I-125 seeds for localization of nonpalpable breast lesions. <em>Acad Radiol</em> 2006;13(7):909–915.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.acra.2006.03.017">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16777565/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Radiation+safety+with+use+of+I-125+seeds+for+localization+of+nonpalpable+breast+lesions&amp;author=W+Pavlicek&amp;author=HA+Walton&amp;author=PJ+Karstaedt&amp;author=RJ+Gray&amp;publication_year=2006&amp;journal=Acad+Radiol&amp;pages=909-915&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.acra.2006.03.017&amp;pmid=16777565">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">7.</div><div id="r7" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Iodine-125 and palladium-103 low dose rate brachytherapy seeds used for localization of non-palpable lesions. United States Nuclear Regulatory Commission. <a href="http://www.nrc.gov/materials/miau/med-use-toolkit/seed-localization.html">http://www.nrc.gov/materials/miau/med-use-toolkit/seed-localization.html</a>. Updated February 24, 2014. Accessed July 22, 2014.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=United+States+Nuclear+Regulatory+Commission&amp;author=Iodine-125+and+palladium-103+low+dose+rate+brachytherapy+seeds+used+for+localization+of+non-palpable+lesions">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">8.</div><div id="r8" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Lovrics PJ, Goldsmith CH, Hodgson N, et al. A multicentered, randomized, controlled trial comparing radioguided seed localization to standard wire localization for nonpalpable, invasive and in situ breast carcinomas. <em>Ann Surg Oncol</em> 2011;18(12):3407–3414.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1245/s10434-011-1699-y">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21533657/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=A+multicentered%2C+randomized%2C+controlled+trial+comparing+radioguided+seed+localization+to+standard+wire+localization+for+nonpalpable%2C+invasive+and+in+situ+breast+carcinomas&amp;author=PJ+Lovrics&amp;author=CH+Goldsmith&amp;author=N+Hodgson&amp;publication_year=2011&amp;journal=Ann+Surg+Oncol&amp;pages=3407-3414&amp;doi=10.1245%2Fs10434-011-1699-y&amp;pmid=21533657">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">9.</div><div id="r9" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Lovrics PJ, Cornacchi SD, Vora R, Goldsmith CH, Kahnamoui K. Systematic review of radioguided surgery for non-palpable breast cancer. <em>Eur J Surg Oncol</em> 2011;37(5):388–397.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ejso.2011.01.018">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21333482/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Systematic+review+of+radioguided+surgery+for+non-palpable+breast+cancer&amp;author=PJ+Lovrics&amp;author=SD+Cornacchi&amp;author=R+Vora&amp;author=CH+Goldsmith&amp;author=K+Kahnamoui&amp;publication_year=2011&amp;journal=Eur+J+Surg+Oncol&amp;pages=388-397&amp;doi=10.1016%2Fj.ejso.2011.01.018&amp;pmid=21333482">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">10.</div><div id="r10" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Rao R, Moldrem A, Sarode V, et al. Experience with seed localization for nonpalpable breast lesions in a public health care system. <em>Ann Surg Oncol</em> 2010;17(12):3241–3246.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core